@startuml bdd-architecture
!theme plain

title **BDD Test Architecture with Cypress + Cucumber + POM**

' Components
package "1. Feature File (*.feature)" as FEATURE #LightBlue
package "2. Page Object (POM)" as POM #LightGreen
package "3. Step Definitions" as STEPS #LightYellow
package "4. Hooks (Setup/Teardown)" as HOOKS #LightGray
package "5. World (optional)" as WORLD #LightCoral

' Relationships
FEATURE --> STEPS : "describes scenarios (Gherkin)"
STEPS --> POM : "use static selector strings"
HOOKS --> STEPS : "Before/After per scenario"
STEPS --> WORLD : "access scenario data via this"
WORLD --> HOOKS : "populated in Before hook"

' Explanatory notes
note right of FEATURE
  **Example:** login.feature
  Contains scenarios in
  Given/When/Then format. It is the
  executable specification.
end note

note right of POM
  **Example:** LoginPage.ts
  Exports static selector strings only.
  Example:
  static emailInput = "[data-testid='email']"
  Steps import these — never hardcode selectors.
end note

note right of STEPS
  **Example:** login.steps.ts
  Maps each Gherkin step to
  Cypress commands (cy.get, cy.click, etc.)
  using Page Object selectors.
  Delegates UI logic.
end note

note right of HOOKS
  **Example:** hooks.ts
  Before/After from @badeball/
  cypress-cucumber-preprocessor.
  NO browser launch — Cypress handles it.
  Use for: cookies, API seed data, screenshots.
end note

note right of WORLD
  **Example:** world.ts (optional)
  Shared scenario-scoped data only.
  No browser/page/context management.
  Use when steps pass data between each other
  (e.g., this.orderId created in Given,
  read in Then).
end note

' Execution flow
note bottom of HOOKS
  **Cypress Flow:**
  1. Cypress opens browser automatically.
  2. Before hook runs (cookies, seed data).
  3. Cucumber reads Feature → executes Steps.
  4. Steps use cy.* commands + Page Objects.
  5. After hook runs (screenshots on failure).
  6. Cypress closes browser automatically.
end note

@enduml
